/SCC/XXOMMENTARY/XX. In the ancient Near East, free people wore fringes, or
/ITtzitzit/XX, on the hems of their everyday clothes. Since only free people wore
/ITtzitzit/XX, they were a form of identification. Business transactions were sealed
by kissing the /ITtzitzit/XX./PR
/PR
The mitzvah of /ITtzitzit/XX is based on that ancient sign of freedom. The fringes
remind us that we voluntarily follow the way of God, who freed us from
Egyptian slavery. It is, literally, a string tied around our finger.    /SC/XXL.W.K./XX/PR
/PR
çâòñé / /ITMitzrayim/XX was the escaping HebrewsÚ, not the EgyptiansÚ, name for
the land of Egypt: perhaps a slave-term, and probably not of Semitic ori-
gin, it has associations with the root òòñ, to be in distress, constricted, in
anguish, or in dire straits. This word powerfully evokes the choking
oppression of slavery. As the psalmist wrote: Ñâ âöÄòó òñéÑ èé / From the
depths I called to Yah.    /SC/XXM.P./XX/PR
